description: Hook architecture, orchestration, and composition constraints
globs:
  - "features/**/*"
  - "shared/hooks/**/*"
alwaysApply: true
---

# hooks.mdc

- Hooks must live inside a dedicated `hooks/` or `hook/` directory
- Keep hooks colocated with their owning feature
- Avoid placing feature business hooks inside `shared/`
- Shared hooks must remain domain-agnostic
- Separate UI hooks from business hooks
- Avoid mixing UI state with business workflows

## Responsibilities

- Hooks must encapsulate a single responsibility
- Avoid oversized hooks
- Avoid catch-all hooks
- Avoid mixing unrelated concerns inside the same hook
- Hooks manage state, effects, orchestration, and business interaction
- Components must remain presentation-focused
- Avoid embedding orchestration logic directly inside components

## Hook composition

- Prefer composing multiple focused hooks
- Avoid duplicating stateful logic across components
- Prefer orchestration hooks when multiple hooks must coordinate
- Hooks must communicate through explicit inputs and outputs
- Avoid hidden dependencies between composed hooks
- Avoid implicit shared mutable state between hooks

## Orchestrator hooks

- Create an orchestrator hook when a component uses more than 2 business hooks
- Orchestrator hooks coordinate communication between hooks
- Orchestrator hooks centralize derived state
- Orchestrator hooks centralize business orchestration
- Components must consume orchestrated state instead of coordinating hooks directly
- Prefer a single orchestrator hook entrypoint per complex component
- Orchestrator hooks must expose only the final UI-facing API
- Avoid leaking internal hook details to components
- Orchestrator hooks coordinate hooks, not replace them
- Avoid placing all business logic inside orchestrators
- Keep orchestrators thin and composition-oriented

### Good

```ts
const {
  prescriptionForm,
  lensSide,
  indexSelect,
  calculatedLensThickness,
} = useSimulatorOrchestrator();
```

### Bad

```ts
const prescriptionForm = usePrescriptionForm();
const lensSide = useLensSide();
const indexSelect = useIndexSelect();
```

## Derived state

- Centralize derived state inside hooks or orchestrators
- Avoid recalculating business state inside JSX
- Avoid duplicating derived state across hooks
- Prefer derived state over duplicated synchronized state

## Effects

- Avoid unnecessary `useEffect` usage
- Prefer derived state over synchronization effects
- Avoid effect chains between hooks
- Avoid syncing duplicated state
- Keep effects narrowly scoped and explicit

## Async coordination

- Keep async coordination inside hooks
- Components must not orchestrate async workflows
- Centralize loading and error states inside hooks

## Hook APIs

- Expose explicit return values
- Prefer object returns for business hooks
- Avoid unstable return structures
- Keep hook APIs predictable and narrowly scoped
- Avoid exposing implementation details

## File structure

- Keep one primary responsibility per hook file
- Avoid multiple unrelated hooks inside the same file
- Prefer explicit hook entrypoints

## Naming

- Hooks must start with `use`
- Hook names must describe domain responsibility
- Orchestrator hooks should explicitly communicate orchestration intent

### Good

```ts
useSimulatorOrchestrator;
usePrescriptionForm;
useLensSide;
```

### Bad

```ts
useManager;
useData;
useEverything;
```

## Anti-patterns

- Avoid hooks that control unrelated workflows
- Avoid hooks that only proxy values without responsibility
- Avoid deeply nested hook dependency chains
- Avoid business orchestration directly inside pages or components
- Avoid massive hooks replacing proper composition